== Concept cars ==
[[File:Nissan Ariya Concept.jpg|thumb|Ariya concept (front)|alt=Ariya Concept (front)|left]]
[[File:Nissan Ariya Concept rear.jpg|alt=Ariya concept (rear)|thumb|Ariya Concept (rear)]]
The Nissan Ariya [[concept car]] was presented on 24 October 2019 at the [[Tokyo Motor Show#2019|2019 Tokyo Motor Show]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Paukert |first=Chris |date=23 October 2019 |title=Nissan Ariya Concept previews the Leafmaker's new crossover EV |url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/nissan-ariya-concept-ev-tokyo-motor-show/ |access-date=15 July 2020 |work=[[CNET|Roadshow by CNET]]}}</ref> It is a 100% electric coupe SUV concept car measuring {{cvt|4.6|m}} in length.{{citation needed|date=July 2020}} The concept car was fitted with 21-inch rims, LED headlamps and an illuminated logo on its grille,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Christopher |date=23 October 2019 |title=Nissan Ariya Concept Previews Future Midsize EV Crossover |url=https://www.motor1.com/news/377919/nissan-ariya-concept-future-ev-crossover/ |access-date=15 July 2020 |work=[[Motorsport Network|Motor1.com]]}}</ref> which itself takes the form of a large "V" characteristic of Nissan design. Inside, the dashboard is equipped with two 12.3-inch screens assembled to form a large screen, from which ProPilot 2.0, the second generation of Nissan's [[driver assistance]] system,<ref>{{cite web |title=ProPILOT 2.0 |url=https://www.nissan-global.com/EN/TECHNOLOGY/OVERVIEW/ad2.html |access-date=25 November 2021 |website=Nissan Global}}</ref> is controlled. The manufacturer has not distributed information on the capacity of the battery to be used in the production Ariya, but indicated that it will be recharged by direct current (DC) compatible with standard [[CHAdeMO]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gnaticov |first=Cristian |date=21 October 2019 |title=Nissan Ariya Concept Previews Rogue-Sized Electric SUV For America And Beyond |url=https://www.carscoops.com/2019/10/nissan-ariya-concept-previews-rogue-sized-electric-suv-for-america-and-beyond/ |access-date=15 July 2020 |website=Carscoops}}</ref> It will accelerate from [[0 to 60 mph|zero to 60 miles per hour]] in 5.1 seconds.<ref name="wsj1" /> The Ariya will support the CCS standard in the US and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Goodwin |first=Antuan |title=Cheerio, CHAdeMO: Nissan adopts CCS fast-charging with new Ariya electric SUV |url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/nissan-ariya-electric-suv-adopts-ccs-fast-charging/ |access-date=2021-05-17 |website=Roadshow |language=en}}</ref>

=== Ariya Single Seater ===
[[File:Nissan ARIYA single seater concept, 2021.jpg|thumb|Ariya Single Seater Concept]]

The Ariya Single Seater Concept was unveiled in December 2021, as part of the manufacturer's Futures event. The concept car, which is a demonstration of an all-electric motorsports vehicle similar to ones used in [[Formula E]] racing, shares its powertrain with the Ariya SUV. The concept also shares multiple design cues with its SUV counterpart, including the illuminated "V" shape at its front and its overall form, which, according to the Nissan, "looks like it was shaped by the air itself". Tommaso Volpe, who is the manufacturer's global motorsports director, stated that the Ariya Single Seater Concept acts as "a powerful demonstration of just how thrilling electric vehicles could be."<ref>{{cite web |date=2 December 2021 |title=Nissan reveals high-performance Ariya Single Seater Concept |url=https://global.nissannews.com/en/releases/nissan-ariya-single-seater-concept |access-date=5 December 2021 |website=Nissan Official Global Newsroom}}</ref>{{clear}}

